The '''Kragujevac massacre''' was the [[mass murder]] of between 2,778 and 2,794&nbsp;mostly [[Serbs|Serb]] men and boys in [[Kragujevac]]{{efn|{{lang-sr-cyr|Крагујевац}}, {{IPA-sh|krǎɡujeʋat͡s|pron|Kragujevac.ogg}}}} by [[Nazi Germany|German]] soldiers on 21&nbsp;October 1941. It occurred in the [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia|German-occupied territory of Serbia]] during [[World War II]], and came in [[reprisal]] for insurgent attacks in the [[Gornji Milanovac]] district that resulted in the deaths of 10&nbsp;German soldiers and the wounding of 26&nbsp;others. The number of hostages to be shot was calculated as a ratio of 100&nbsp;hostages executed for every German soldier killed and 50&nbsp;hostages executed for every German soldier wounded, a formula devised by [[Adolf Hitler]] with the intent of suppressing anti-Nazi resistance in Eastern Europe.

After a punitive operation was conducted in the surrounding villages, during which 422&nbsp;males were shot and four villages burned down, another 70&nbsp;male [[Jews]] and [[communism|communists]] who had been arrested in Kragujevac were shot. Simultaneously, males between the ages of 16&nbsp;and 60, including high school students, were assembled by German troops and local [[collaborationism|collaborators]], and the victims were selected from amongst them. The selected males were then marched to fields outside the city, shot with heavy [[machine gun]]s, and their bodies buried in [[mass grave]]s. Contemporary German military records indicate that 2,300&nbsp;hostages were shot. After the war, inflated estimates ranged as high as 7,000&nbsp;deaths, but German and Serbian scholars have now agreed on the figure of nearly 2,800&nbsp;killed, including 144&nbsp;high school students. As well as Serbs, massacre victims included Jews, [[Romani people in Serbia|Romani people]], [[Islam in Serbia|Muslims]], [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]], [[Slovenes]] and members of other nationalities.

Several senior German military officials were tried and convicted for their involvement in the reprisal shootings at the [[Nuremberg trials]] and the [[subsequent Nuremberg trials]]. The massacre had a profound effect on the course of the [[World War II in Yugoslavia|war in Yugoslavia]]. It exacerbated tensions between the two guerrilla movements, the communist-led [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisans]] and the royalist, [[Serbian nationalism|Serbian nationalist]] [[Chetniks]], and convinced Chetnik leader [[Draža Mihailović]] that further attacks against the Germans would only result in more Serb civilian deaths. The Germans soon found mass executions of Serbs to be ineffectual and counterproductive, as they tended to drive the population into the arms of insurgents. The ratio of 100&nbsp;executions for one soldier killed and 50&nbsp;executions for one soldier wounded was reduced by half in February 1943, and removed altogether later in the year. The massacre is commemorated by the [[October in Kragujevac Memorial Park]] and the co-located 21st&nbsp;October Museum, and has been the subject of several poems and feature films. The day the massacre took place is commemorated annually in Serbia as the Day of Remembrance of the Serbian Victims of World War II.

==Background==
===Encirclement and invasion of Yugoslavia===
Following the 1938 ''[[Anschluss]]'' between [[Nazi Germany]] and [[First Austrian Republic|Austria]], Yugoslavia came to share its northwestern border with Germany and fell under increasing pressure as its neighbours aligned themselves with the [[Axis powers]]. In April 1939, Italy opened a second frontier with Yugoslavia when it [[Italian invasion of Albania|invaded]] and occupied neighbouring [[Albanian Kingdom (1928–39)|Albania]].{{sfn|Roberts|1973|pp=6–7}} At the outbreak of World War&nbsp;II, the Yugoslav government declared its [[Neutrality (international relations)|neutrality]].{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=8}} Between September and November 1940, [[Kingdom of Hungary (1920–46)|Hungary]] and [[Kingdom of Romania|Romania]] joined the [[Tripartite Pact]], aligning themselves with the Axis, and Italy [[Greco-Italian War|invaded Greece]]. Yugoslavia was by then almost completely surrounded by the Axis powers and their satellites, and its neutral stance toward the war became strained.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|pp=6–7}} In late February 1941, [[Kingdom of Bulgaria|Bulgaria]] joined the Pact. The following day, German troops entered Bulgaria from Romania, closing the ring around Yugoslavia.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=12}} Intending to secure his southern flank for the [[Operation Barbarossa|impending attack]] on the [[Soviet Union]], German dictator [[Adolf Hitler]] began placing heavy pressure on Yugoslavia to join the Axis. On 25&nbsp;March 1941, after some delay, the Yugoslav government conditionally signed the Pact. Two days later, a group of pro-Western, [[Serbian nationalism|Serbian nationalist]] [[Royal Yugoslav Air Force]] officers deposed the country's [[regent]], [[Prince Paul of Yugoslavia|Prince Paul]], in a bloodless [[Yugoslav coup d'état|coup d'état]]. They placed his teenage nephew [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Peter]] on the throne and brought to power a "government of national unity" led by the head of the Royal Yugoslav Air Force, General [[Dušan Simović]].{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|pp=10–13}} The coup enraged Hitler, who immediately ordered the country's [[invasion of Yugoslavia|invasion]], which commenced on 6&nbsp;April 1941.{{sfn|Roberts|1973|p=15}}

Yugoslavia was quickly overwhelmed by the combined strength of the Axis powers and surrendered in less than two weeks. The government and royal family went into exile, and the country was occupied and dismembered by its neighbours. The [[Territory of the Military Commander in Serbia|German-occupied territory of Serbia]] was limited to the pre-[[Balkan Wars|Balkan War]] borders of the [[Kingdom of Serbia]] and was directly occupied by the Germans for the key rail and riverine transport routes that passed through it, as well as its valuable resources, particularly [[non-ferrous metals]].{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=49}} The occupied territory covered about {{convert|51,000|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} and had a population of 3.8&nbsp;million. Hitler had briefly considered erasing all existence of a Serbian state, but this was quickly abandoned and the Germans began searching for a Serb suitable to lead a [[puppet government]] in Belgrade.{{sfn|Ramet|Lazić|2011|pp=19–20}} They initially settled on [[Milan Aćimović]], a staunch [[anti-communism|anti-communist]] who served as Yugoslavia's [[Ministry of the Interior (Yugoslavia)|Minister of Internal Affairs]] in late 1939 and early 1940.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=177–178}}

===Occupation and resistance===
[[File:Territory Of The German Military Commander In Serbia 1941-44.png|thumb|right|upright=1|alt=Wartime map of Serbia|Map of German-occupied Serbia]]
Two resistance movements emerged following the invasion: the [[League of Communists of Yugoslavia|communist]]-led, multi-ethnic [[Yugoslav Partisans|Partisans]], and the royalist, Serbian nationalist [[Chetniks]], although during 1941, within the occupied territory, even the Partisans consisted almost entirely of Serbs. The Partisans were led by the [[President of the League of Communists of Yugoslavia|General Secretary of the Communist Party of Yugoslavia]], [[Josip Broz Tito]]; the Chetniks were led by [[Colonel]] [[Draža Mihailović]], an officer in the interwar [[Royal Yugoslav Army]]. The two movements had widely divergent goals. Whereas the Partisans sought to turn Yugoslavia into a communist state under Tito's leadership, the Chetniks sought a return to the pre-war ''[[status quo]]'', whereby the Yugoslav monarchy—and, by extension, Serb political hegemony—would be restored.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|pp=59–60}} Communist resistance commenced in early July, shortly after the [[Operation Barbarossa|invasion of the Soviet Union]], targeting both the Germans and the puppet authorities.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|pp=177–178}} By late August 1941, the Partisans and Chetniks were carrying out joint attacks against the Germans.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|pp=59–60}} The Partisans were well organised and many of their commanders had ample military experience, having fought in the [[Spanish Civil War]]. Within several months of the invasion, they had 8,000&nbsp;fighters spread across 21&nbsp;[[detachment (military)|detachments]] in Serbia alone.{{sfn|Shepherd|2016|p=198}} Many Chetniks were either veterans of the Balkan Wars and World War&nbsp;I or former members of the Royal Yugoslav Army.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|pp=118–123}} They boasted around 20,000&nbsp;fighters in the German-occupied territory of Serbia at the time of the massacre.{{sfn|Lampe|2000|p=217}}

On 29&nbsp;August, the Germans replaced Aćimović with another fervent anti-communist, the former [[Ministry of Defense (Yugoslavia)|Minister of the Army and Navy]] and [[Chief of the General Staff (Yugoslavia)|Chief of the General Staff]], General [[Milan Nedić]], who formed a [[Government of National Salvation|new puppet government]].{{sfn|Ramet|Lazić|2011|p=22}} In September, the Nedić government was permitted to form the [[Serbian Volunteer Corps (World War II)|Serbian Volunteer Command]] ({{lang-sh|Srpska dobrovoljačka komanda}}; SDK), an auxiliary [[paramilitary]] formation to help quell anti-German resistance. In effect, the SDK was the military arm of the [[Fascism|fascist]] [[Yugoslav National Movement]] ({{lang-sh-Latn|links=no|Združena borbena organizacija rada}}, ''Zbor''), led by [[Dimitrije Ljotić]].{{sfn|Cohen|1996|p=38}} It was originally intended to have a strength of 3,000–4,000&nbsp;troops, but this number eventually rose to 12,000.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|pp=58–59}} It was headed by [[Kosta Mušicki]], a former colonel in the Royal Yugoslav Army, whom Nedić appointed on 6&nbsp;October 1941.{{sfn|Cohen|1996|p=37}} In the early stages of the occupation, the SDK formed the bulk of Nedić's forces, which numbered around 20,000&nbsp;men by late 1941.{{sfn|Milazzo|1975|p=28}}

==Prelude==
===Anti-German uprising===
{{main|Uprising in Serbia (1941)}}
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-H30220, Wilhelm Keitel.jpg|thumb|upright=1|''Generalfeldmarschall'' [[Wilhelm Keitel]] of the [[OKW]] issued Hitler's order regarding the ratio of hostages to be shot. After the war, he was convicted of [[war crimes]] and [[crimes against humanity]], and executed in 1946.|alt=a black and white image of a man in uniform]]
Nedić's inability to crush the Partisans and Chetniks prompted the Military Commander in Serbia to request German reinforcements from other parts of the continent.{{sfn|Milazzo|1975|p=28}} In mid-September, they transferred the 125th Infantry Regiment from Greece and the [[342nd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|342nd Infantry Division]] from France to help put down the uprising in Serbia. On 16&nbsp;September, Hitler issued Directive No.&nbsp;312 to ''[[Generalfeldmarschall]]'' ([[Field Marshal]]) [[Wilhelm List]], the ''[[Wehrmacht]]'' commander in Southeast Europe, ordering him to suppress all resistance in that part of the continent. That same day, the [[Oberkommando der Wehrmacht|Supreme Command of the Armed Forces]] (''Oberkommando der Wehrmacht''; OKW) issued Hitler's order on the suppression of "Communist Armed Resistance Movements in the Occupied Areas", signed by ''Generalfeldmarschall'' [[Wilhelm Keitel]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=146}} This decree specified that all attacks against the Germans on the [[Eastern Front (World War II)|Eastern Front]] were to be "regarded as being of communist origin", and that 100&nbsp;hostages were to be shot for every German soldier killed and 50&nbsp;were to be shot for every German soldier wounded.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=140}}{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=61}} It was intended to apply to all of [[Eastern Europe]], though an identical policy had already been implemented in Serbia as early as 28&nbsp;April 1941, aimed at deterring guerrilla attacks. Attacks against the Germans increased in the first half of the year and Serbia once again became a warzone. German troops fanned through the countryside burning villages, taking hostages and establishing concentration camps. The first mass executions of hostages commenced in July.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=61}}

The strengthening of Germany's military presence in Serbia resulted in a new wave of mass executions and [[war crime]]s. The commanders who bore the most responsibility for these atrocities were primarily of Austrian origin and had served in the [[Austro-Hungarian Army]] during [[World War I]].{{sfn|Lampe|2000|p=215}} Most were ardently [[Anti-Serb sentiment|anti-Serb]], a prejudice that the historian [[Stevan K. Pavlowitch]] links to the Nazis' wider anti-[[Slavs|Slavic]] racism.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|pp=60–61}}

On 19&nbsp;September, ''[[General der Gebirgstruppe]]'' ([[Lieutenant General]]) [[Franz Böhme]] was appointed as Plenipotentiary Commanding General in Serbia, with direct responsibility for quelling the revolt, bringing with him the staff of [[XVIII Army Corps (Wehrmacht)|XVIII&nbsp;Mountain Corps]]. He was allocated additional forces to assist him in doing so, reinforcing the three German occupation divisions already in the territory.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|pp=97–98}} These divisions were the [[104th Jäger Division (Wehrmacht)|704th Infantry Division]], [[114th Jäger Division (Wehrmacht)|714th Infantry Division]] and [[117th Jäger Division (Wehrmacht)|717th Infantry Division]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=96}} Böhme boasted a profound hatred of Serbs and encouraged his predominantly Austrian-born troops to exact "vengeance" against them. His primary grievances were the [[Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria|assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand]] and subsequent Austro-Hungarian military defeats at the hands of the [[Royal Serbian Army]], which he thought could only be rectified by the reprisal shooting of Serbian civilians. "Your objective," Böhme declared, "is to be achieved in a land where, in 1914, streams of German blood flowed because of the treachery of the Serbs, men and women. You are the avengers of those dead."{{sfn|Shepherd|2016|p=199}}

===Clash at Gornji Milanovac===
[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-J21813, Franz Böhme.jpg|thumb|upright=1|''General der Gebirgstruppe'' [[Franz Böhme]] was furious when his orders to burn down Gornji Milanovac and take hostages were not carried out. After the war, he committed suicide before his arraignment on war crimes charges.|alt=a black and white image of a male in uniform]]
On 28&nbsp;September, the 6th Company of the German 920th ''Landesschützen'' (Local Defence) Battalion was captured by insurgents in the town of [[Gornji Milanovac]].{{sfn|von Bischofhausen|1950|pp=980–981}}{{sfn|Manoschek|1995|pp=158–159}} According to the journalist [[Misha Glenny]], the Partisans launched an attack on a small German detachment based at a local school. They did not expect to capture the German garrison, but undertook the attack in order to generate new recruits from the surrounding area. The local Chetnik commander, Zvonimir Vučković, became aware of the Partisan plans and decided to join in the attack to avoid the significant loss of prestige that would result from allowing the Partisans to attack alone. The insurgents launched a morning attack against the school. Although they were successful in overrunning the sentry posts, the Germans' heavy [[machine gun]]s soon stopped the assault. In 90&nbsp;minutes of fighting, 10&nbsp;Germans were killed and 26&nbsp;wounded. The two insurgent groups judged that continuing the assault would be too costly and Vučković suggested negotiating with the Germans. To the insurgents' surprise, the Germans surrendered. They were then taken away by Vučković and his men.{{sfn|Glenny|2001|pp=491–492}}

A German officer who escaped reported that the German prisoners were being humanely treated, but when Böhme became aware of the situation, he decided that retaliation was needed.{{sfn|Manoschek|1995|pp=158–159}}{{sfn|Glenny|2001|pp=491–492}} He ordered III.&nbsp;Battalion of the 749th Infantry Regiment, part of the [[117th Jäger Division (Wehrmacht)|717th Infantry Division]], to burn down Gornji Milanovac and take hostages in order to expedite the recovery of the captured German troops. Due to a misunderstanding by the battalion commander, the unit did not burn down the town on 6&nbsp;October, and released the 170&nbsp;hostages it had arrested. Böhme was furious, and on 15&nbsp;October, he sent the same battalion back to Gornji Milanovac to carry out his original orders. This was done on 16&nbsp;October.{{sfn|Manoschek|1995|pp=158–159}}

===Kraljevo massacre===
{{main article|Kraljevo massacre}}
On 15–16&nbsp;October,{{sfn|Browning|2007|p=343}} 10&nbsp;German soldiers were killed and 14&nbsp;wounded during a joint Partisan-Chetnik attack on [[Kraljevo]], a city about {{convert|150|km}} south of [[Belgrade]] and {{convert|50|km}} southeast of Gornji Milanovac.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=62}} On 15&nbsp;October, troops of the 717th Infantry Division shot 300&nbsp;civilians from Kraljevo in reprisal.{{sfn|Shepherd|2012|loc=p. 306, note 109}} These reprisal killings continued over the following days, and by 17&nbsp;or 20&nbsp;October,{{sfn|Browning|2007|p=343}}{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=62}} German troops had rounded up and shot 1,736&nbsp;men and 19&nbsp;"communist" women from the city and its outskirts,{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|loc=p. 146, note 92}}{{sfn|Levene|2013|p=84}} despite attempts by local collaborationists to mitigate the punishment.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=62}} These executions were personally supervised by the commander of the 717th Infantry Division, ''[[Generalmajor]]'' ([[Brigadier general|Brigadier General]]) [[Paul Hoffmann (general)|Paul Hoffman]].{{sfn|Shepherd|2012|p=140}}

==Timeline==
===Round-up===
Kragujevac is an [[industrial district|industrial city]] in [[Central Serbia]], about {{convert|100|km}} south of Belgrade,{{sfn|Mazower|2002|p=7}} and {{convert|37|km}} east of Gornji Milanovac.{{sfn|Glenny|2001|p=492}} It had a population of more than 40,000&nbsp;in 1941,{{sfn|Jorgić|2013|p=79}} and was the headquarters of a German military district.{{sfn|Glenny|2001|p=492}} The city was also home to [[Zastava Arms|Yugoslavia's largest armaments factory]], which had between 7,000 and 8,000 workers before the invasion.{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=624}}

A report was written by the military district commander in Kragujevac, ''[[Hauptmann]]'' ([[Captain (armed forces)|Captain]]) Otto von Bischofhausen, immediately after the massacre. This report was addressed to Böhme, and was later tendered in evidence at the [[Subsequent Nuremberg trials]]. According to von Bischofhausen, in the late evening of 18&nbsp;October, all male [[Jews]] in Kragujevac, along with some communists, were arrested according to lists, totalling 70&nbsp;persons. As this constituted far too few hostages to meet the quota of 2,300, it was proposed to collect the balance by arrests on the streets, squares and houses of Kragujevac, in an operation to be conducted by III./749th Infantry Regiment, and I.&nbsp;Battalion of the 724th Infantry Regiment, part of the 704th Infantry Division. In response to this proposal, von Bischofhausen claimed that he suggested to the garrison commander, [[Major]] Paul König, that, instead of using the population of Kragujevac, the required hostages be gathered from surrounding villages which were known to be "completely strewn with communists".{{sfn|von Bischofhausen|1950|p=981}} According to von Bischofhausen's account, this suggestion was initially accepted by König, and, on 19&nbsp;October, III./749th Infantry Regiment "mopped up" the villages of Mečkovac and Maršić, and I./724th Infantry Regiment conducted a similar operation in the villages of [[Grošnica]] and Milatovac. A total of 422&nbsp;men were shot in these four villages, without any German losses.{{sfn|von Bischofhausen|1950|pp=981–982}}

On the evening of 19&nbsp;October, von Bischofhausen again met with König and was told that the original proposal was to be implemented the following day in order to collect the 2,300&nbsp;hostages. The following evening, the male Jews and communists, who had been held without food since their arrest, were shot by German troops at the barracks and courtyard where they were being held.{{sfn|Glenny|2001|p=492}} Simultaneously, males between the ages of 16&nbsp;and 60&nbsp;were arrested within Kragujevac itself.{{sfn|von Bischofhausen|1950|p=982}}{{sfn|Prusin|2017|p=97}} They were detained in the barracks of a former motorised battalion at Stanovija Field.{{sfn|Glenny|2001|p=492}} Over 7,000&nbsp;hostages were assembled.{{sfn|Byford|2011a|loc=pp. 126–127, note 35}} German troops and [[Germans of Yugoslavia|ethnic German]] units from the [[Banat (1941–44)|Banat]] were involved in the round-up,{{sfn|Lampe|2000|p=217}} as was the Fifth Regiment of the SDK, under the command of Marisav Petrović.{{sfn|Cohen|1996|p=38}} According to von Bischofhausen, König permitted several classes of males to be excluded from the round-up, including those with a special pass issued by von Bischofhausen's district headquarters, members of a vital profession or trade, and those who were members of Ljotić's movement.{{sfn|von Bischofhausen|1950|p=982}}{{efn|Those excluded on the basis of their profession included medical personnel, pharmacists and technicians.{{sfn|Prusin|2017|p=97}}}} When too few adult males could be located, high school students were also rounded up.{{sfn|Lampe|2000|p=217}} Also seized were priests and monks from the city's churches. Each hostage was registered and his belongings noted meticulously.{{sfn|Glenny|2001|p=492}}

===Executions===
[[File:Notification on 21 October 1941.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1|German public notification announcing the shooting of hostages, 21 October 1941]]
The hostages were held overnight on a public plaza in the town. In his version of events, von Bischofhausen claimed that he made objections to König, but the latter insisted that his orders, which had been issued by the commander of the 749th Infantry Regiment, would be carried out.{{sfn|von Bischofhausen|1950|p=982}} Shortly before the executions commenced, Ljotić obtained approval for two ''Zbor'' officials to scrutinise the hostages. Over 3,000&nbsp;individuals, those identified as being "genuine nationalists" and "real patriots", were excluded from the execution lists as a result of Ljotić's intervention.{{sfn|Byford|2011a|loc=pp. 126–127, note 35}} Those who were not extracted from the hostage pool were accused of being communists or spreading "communist propaganda". The ''Zbor'' officials told them they were not "worth saving" because they had "infected the younger generation with their leftist ideas."{{sfn|Antić|2012|p=29}} The Germans considered ''Zbor'''s involvement to be a "nuisance". According to the [[social science|social scientist]] Jovan Byford, it was never intended or likely to reduce the overall number of hostages killed in reprisal, and served only to ensure the exclusion of those that were deemed by ''Zbor'' to be worth saving.{{sfn|Byford|2011a|loc=pp. 126–127, note 35}}

On the morning of 21&nbsp;October, the assembled men and boys were marched to a field outside the town. Over a period of seven hours, they were lined up in groups of 50&nbsp;to 120 and shot with heavy machine guns. "Go ahead and shoot", said an elderly teacher, "I am conducting my class".{{sfn|Lampe|2000|p=217}} He was shot together with his students.{{sfn|Prusin|2017|p=97}} As they faced the [[firing squad]], many hostages sang the patriotic song ''[[Hey, Slavs]]'', which became Yugoslavia's [[national anthem]] after the war.{{sfn|Pavković|Kelen|2016|p=56}} One German soldier was shot for refusing to participate in the killings.{{sfn|West|1995|p=112}} A German report stated: "The executions in Kragujevac occurred although there had been no attacks on members of the Wehrmacht in this city, for the reason that not enough hostages could be found elsewhere."{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|loc=p. 370, note 74}}{{sfn|Singleton|1985|p=194}} Even some German [[informant]]s were inadvertently killed.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|loc=p. 370, note 74}} "Clearly", the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] historian Mark Levene writes, "Germans in uniform were not ''that'' particular about who they shot in reprisal, especially in the Balkans, where the populace were deemed subhuman."{{sfn|Levene|2013|p=84}}

Following the massacre, the Germans held a military parade through the city centre.{{sfn|Glenny|2001|p=493}} On 31&nbsp;October, Böhme sent a report to the acting Wehrmacht commander in Southeast Europe, ''[[General der Pioniere]]'' (Lieutenant General) [[Walter Kuntze]], reporting that 2,300&nbsp;hostages had been shot in Kragujevac.{{sfn|Nuremberg Military Tribunals|1950|pp=767 & 1277}}

==Aftermath==
===Response===
The Partisan commander and later historian [[Milovan Djilas]] recalled how the Kragujevac massacre gripped all of Serbia in "deadly terror".{{sfn|Mazower|2008|p=483}} Throughout the war, local collaborators pressured the Germans to implement stringent vetting procedures to ensure that "innocent civilians" were not executed, though only when the hostages were ethnic Serbs.{{sfn|Byford|2011a|p=306}}{{sfn|Byford|2011b|p=120}} By the time Böhme was relieved as Plenipotentiary Commanding General in December 1941, between 20,000 and 30,000 civilians had been killed in German reprisal shootings.{{sfn|Manoschek|2000|p=178}} The ratio of 100&nbsp;executions for each soldier killed and 50&nbsp;executions for each soldier wounded was reduced by half in February 1943, and removed altogether later in the year. Henceforth, each individual execution had to be approved by Special Envoy [[Hermann Neubacher]].{{sfn|Tomasevich|2001|p=69}} The massacres in Kragujevac and Kraljevo caused German military commanders in Serbia to question the efficacy of such killings, as they pushed thousands of Serbs into the hands of anti-German guerrillas. In Kraljevo, the entire Serbian workforce of an airplane factory producing armaments for the Germans was shot. This helped convince the OKW that arbitrary shootings of Serbs not only incurred a significant political cost but were also counterproductive.{{sfn|Mazower|2004|p=154}}{{sfn|Browning|2007|p=344}}

The killings at Kragujevac and Kraljevo exacerbated tensions between the Partisans and Chetniks.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=62}} They also convinced Mihailović that active resistance was futile for as long as the Germans held an unassailable military advantage in the Balkans, and that killing German troops would only result in the unnecessary deaths of tens of thousands of Serbs. He therefore decided to scale back Chetnik guerrilla attacks and wait for an Allied landing in the Balkans.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|p=146}}{{sfn|Milazzo|1975|p=31}}{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|p=63}} The killings occurred only a few days before Captain [[Bill Hudson (British Army officer)|Bill Hudson]], a [[Special Operations Executive]] officer, met with Mihailović at his [[Ravna Gora (Suvobor)|Ravna Gora]] headquarters.{{sfn|Lampe|2000|p=217}} Hudson witnessed the aftermath of the massacre and noted the psychological toll it exacted. "Morning and night was the most desolating atmosphere," he recounted, "because the women were out in the fields, and every sunrise and sunset you would hear the wails. This had a very strong effect on Mihailović."{{sfn|Williams|2003|p=61}} "The tragedy gave to Nedić convincing proof that the Serbs would be biologically exterminated if they were not submissive," Djilas wrote, "and to the Chetniks proof that the Partisans were prematurely provoking the Germans".{{sfn|Mazower|2008|p=483}} Mihailović's decision to refrain from attacking the Germans led to a rift with Tito and the Partisans. The Chetniks' non-resistance made it easier for the Germans to confront the Partisans, who for much of the remainder of the war could not defeat them in open combat.{{sfn|Shepherd|2016|p=200}}

===Legal proceedings and casualty estimates===
[[File:List Indictment.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1|[[Wilhelm List]] is handed the indictment in the [[Hostages Trial]], 12 May 1947]]
List and Böhme were both captured at the end of the war. On 10&nbsp;May 1947, they were charged with war crimes and crimes against humanity as part of the [[Hostages Trial]] of the subsequent Nuremberg trials.{{sfn|Nuremberg Military Tribunals|1950|p=759}} One of the crimes specifically listed in Count&nbsp;1 of the indictment was the massacre of 2,300&nbsp;hostages in Kragujevac.{{sfn|Nuremberg Military Tribunals|1950|p=767}} Böhme committed suicide before his [[arraignment]].{{sfn|Nuremberg Military Tribunals|1950|p=759}} List was found guilty on Count&nbsp;1, as well as on another count.{{sfn|Nuremberg Military Tribunals|1950|p=1274}} He was sentenced to [[life imprisonment]] in 1948,{{sfn|Nuremberg Military Tribunals|1950|p=1318}} but was released due to ill health in 1953. Despite this, he lived until June&nbsp;1971.{{sfn|Wistrich|2013|p=159}} Keitel was found guilty of war crimes and crimes against humanity at the [[Nuremberg Trials]], and subsequently hanged.{{sfn|Wistrich|2013|p=137}} Hoffmann, whom the local population dubbed the "butcher of Kraljevo and Kragujevac", was promoted to command the more capable [[352nd Infantry Division (Wehrmacht)|352nd Infantry Division]] in November&nbsp;1941.{{sfn|Browning|1985|loc=p. 100, note 86}} He ended the war as the commander of a [[prisoner-of-war camp]], having been demoted for refusing to shoot deserters in the Ukraine.{{sfn|Shepherd|2012|p=140}} The 717th Infantry Division was reorganised as the 117th Jäger Division later in the war and its troops took part in the [[Massacre of Kalavryta|massacre]] of hundreds of Greek civilians at [[Kalavryta]] in December 1943.{{sfn|Mazower|2004|p=154}}

At least 31&nbsp;mass graves were discovered in Kragujevac and its surroundings after the war.{{sfn|Glenny|2001|pp=492–493}} In 1969, the historian [[Jozo Tomasevich]] wrote that, despite German official sources stating 2,300&nbsp;hostages had been shot, both the Partisans and Chetniks had agreed that the number of victims was about 7,000. He further stated that careful investigation by a Yugoslav university professor in 1967 had put the figure at about 5,000.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1969|loc=p. 370, note 74}} In 1975, Tomasevich noted that some estimates of the number of those killed were as high as 7,000, but that the foremost authority on German terror in Serbia, Venceslav Glišić, placed the figure at about 3,000.{{sfn|Tomasevich|1975|loc=p. 146, note 92}} In 2007, Pavlowitch wrote that inflated figures of 6,000–7,000&nbsp;victims were advanced and widely believed for many years, but that German and Serbian scholars had recently agreed on the figure of 2,778.{{sfn|Pavlowitch|2007|loc=p. 62, note 15}} In the same year, the curator of the 21st&nbsp;October Museum at Kragujevac, Staniša Brkić, published a book listing the names and personal data of 2,794&nbsp;victims.{{sfn|Markovich|2014|loc=p. 139, note 17}} Of the total killed, 144&nbsp;were high school students, and five of the victims were 12&nbsp;years old.{{sfn|Glenny|2001|p=493}} The last living survivor of the massacre, Dragoljub Jovanović, died in October 2018 at the age of 94. He survived despite sustaining 11 bullet wounds and had to have one of his legs amputated. After the war, he was appointed the inaugural director of the 21st&nbsp;October Museum.{{sfn|Radio Television of Serbia 22 October 2018}}

==Legacy==
[[File:Da.se.ne.zaboravi.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1|The ''Interrupted Flight'' monument at the [[October in Kragujevac Memorial Park]]]]
The massacre at Kragujevac came to symbolize the brutality of the German occupation in Yugoslav popular memory.{{sfn|Benz|2006|p=206}} It has drawn comparisons to the Germans' [[Lidice massacre|destruction]] of the Czechoslovak village of [[Lidice]] in June 1942 and the [[Oradour-sur-Glane massacre|massacre]] of the inhabitants of Oradour-sur-Glane, in France, in June 1944.{{sfn|Prusin|2017|p=97}} To commemorate the victims of the Kragujevac massacre, the whole of Šumarice, where the killings took place, was designated a memorial park in 1953. It is now known as the [[October in Kragujevac Memorial Park]], and covers {{convert|353|ha}} encompassing the area that contains the mass graves. The 21st&nbsp;October Museum was founded within the park on 15&nbsp;February 1976. There are also several monuments within the park, including the ''Interrupted Flight'' monument to the murdered high school students and their teachers, and the monuments ''Pain and Defiance'', ''One Hundred for One'', and ''Resistance and Freedom''. The Memorial Park website notes that the victims of the massacre included Serbs, Jews, [[Romani people in Serbia|Romani people]], [[Islam in Serbia|Muslims]], [[Macedonians (ethnic group)|Macedonians]], [[Slovenes]] and members of other nationalities.{{sfn|Memorial Park|2017}} The memorial was damaged during the [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia]] in 1999.{{sfn|Winstone|2010|loc=Serbia}}

The Serbian poet and writer [[Desanka Maksimović]] wrote a poem about the massacre titled ''Krvava bajka'' ("A Bloody Fairy Tale").{{sfn|Hawkesworth|2000|p=209}} The poem was later included in the Yugoslav secondary school curriculum and schoolchildren were required to memorise it.{{sfn|Milojković-Djurić|1997|loc=p. 106, note 5}} It ranks among the most famous Serbian-language poems.{{sfn|Juraga|2002|p=204}} In 1965, the Belgian poet [[Karel Jonckheere]] wrote the poem ''Kinderen met krekelstem'' ("Children with Cricket Voices"), also about the massacre.{{sfn|Bourgeois|1970|p=68}} ''The Blue Butterfly'', a book of poetry by [[Richard Berengarten]], is based on the poet's experiences while visiting Kragujevac in 1985, when a blue butterfly landed on his hand at the entrance to the memorial museum.{{sfn|Derrick|2015|pp=170–171}}

The massacre has been the subject of two feature films: ''Prozvan je i&nbsp;{{nowrap|V-3}}'' (''{{nowrap|V-3}} is Called Out''; 1962){{sfn|Daković|2010|p=393}} and ''Krvava bajka'' (''A Bloody Fairy Tale''; 1969), named after the eponymous poem.{{sfn|Liehm|Liehm|1977|p=431}} In 2012, the [[National Assembly (Serbia)|National Assembly of Serbia]] passed a law declaring 21&nbsp;October a [[public holiday]], the Day of Remembrance of the Serbian Victims of World War&nbsp;II.{{sfn|Radio Television of Serbia 21 October 2012}}

