{{Infobox LGBT rights | location_header = the U.S. Virgin Islands | image = LocationUSVirginIslands.png | caption = [[United States Virgin Islands]] ([[United States|US]]) | legal_status = Legal since 1985 | gender_identity_expression = | recognition_of_relationships = Same-sex marriage since 2015 | recognition_of_relationships_restrictions = | adoption = Since 2015 | discrimination_protections = None }}
[[Lesbian]], [[gay]], [[bisexual]], and [[transgender]] ([[LGBT]]) people in the [[U.S. Virgin Islands]] face legal challenges and discrimination not faced by other people. Same-sex sexual activity is no longer criminalized, and neither is same-sex marriage. The Virgin Islands lacks a [[hate crimes]] statute and provides LGBT residents no protection against discrimination. Following the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court's]] ruling in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'' on June 26, 2015, which found the denial of marriage rights to same-sex couples unconstitutional, same-sex marriage became legal in the islands.
==Laws regarding same-sex sexual activity==
The first anti-gay criminal law was imposed by Denmark, who had purchased the islands, in 1917. In 1957 the law was expanded to prohibit oral sex.
In 1978, the law was challenged in court as being too vague, but the court rejected this argument.
In 1984, the legislature revised its sex crimes statues to allow consenting adults to have a private life. This revision formally took effect a year later.
Same-sex sexual activity has been legal in the U.S. Virgin Islands since 1985, as long as it occurs between consenting adults in private. Initially, the age of consent was set at 16, but this was raised to 18 in 2017.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gay rights map: Notes on the data|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-26016267|accessdate=November 3, 2014|work=BBC News|date=February 5, 2014}}</ref>
==Recognition of same-sex relationships== {{Main|Same-sex marriage in the United States Virgin Islands}} The statutes of the Virgin Islands state that "Marriage is hereby declared to be a civil contract which may be entered into between a male and a female in accordance with the law."<ref>{{cite web|title=Virgin Islands Code 16 V.I.C. ch. 2 § 31 |url=http://www.lexisnexis.com/hottopics/vicode/|accessdate=November 3, 2014|publisher=LexisNexis|work=Virgin Islands Code}}</ref> However, on June 30, 2015, Governor [[Kenneth Mapp]] announced that the territorial government would comply with the U.S. Supreme Court ruling in ''[[Obergefell v. Hodges]]'', recognizing marriage as a fundamental right that cannot be denied to same-sex couples.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gilbert|first1=Ernice|title=Mapp to Issue Executive Order Mandating Gov. Agencies to Comply with Supreme Court's Same-Sex Ruling|url=http://viconsortium.com/featured/mapp-to-issue-executive-order-mandating-gov-agencies-to-comply-with-supreme-courts-same-sex-ruling/|accessdate=July 1, 2015|work=Virgin Islands Consortium|date=June 30, 2015}}</ref>
===History=== In May 2014, Senator Judi Buckley introduced draft legislation in the [[Legislature of the Virgin Islands|legislature]] to establish same-sex marriage. Called the Civil Marriage Equality Act, it would replace the Code's "between a male and a female" with "between two persons". It included language that would allow anyone authorized to perform a wedding ceremony to decline to do so for any reason. She anticipated that it would take several months for its language to be reviewed.<ref name=fierce>{{cite news|accessdate=November 2, 2014 |url=http://m.virginislandsdailynews.com/news/buckley-s-same-sex-marriage-bill-sparks-fierce-debate-1.1716904 |work=Virgin Islands Daily News |date=July 10, 2014 |first=Jenny |last=Kane |title=Buckley's same-sex marriage bill sparks fierce debate |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220055237/http://m.virginislandsdailynews.com/news/buckley-s-same-sex-marriage-bill-sparks-fierce-debate-1.1716904 |archivedate=December 20, 2014 |df= }}</ref> She expected that she and Governor [[John de Jongh]], who she said would sign the legislation, would leave office in January 2015 before the legislation came to a vote.<ref name=unlikely>{{cite news|url=http://stcroixsource.com/content/news/local-news/2014/07/13/buckley-marriage-equality-bill-unlikely-pass-she-leaves-office|first=Susan|last=Ellis|agency=St. Croix Source|title=Buckley: Marriage Equality Bill Unlikely to Pass Before She Leaves Office|date=July 13, 2014|accessdate=November 3, 2014}}</ref> Supporters of the legislation include Liberty Place, an LGBT advocacy organization based on St. Croix.<ref name=fierce/>
In response, a group of church leaders organized [[One Voice Virgin Islands]] to oppose the legislation and plan a petition drive that aimed to collect 50,000 signatures.<ref name=fierce/> The group authored a letter to V.I. officials that some of its members found objectionable because it included the suggestion that some government officials were homosexual.<ref name=fierce/><ref name=unlikely/> The group's president, New Vision Ministries Pastor James Petty of St. Thomas, said: "We do not wish to be America's same-sex paradise".<ref name=fierce/> Pastor Lennox Zamore said that he rejected the argument that legalizing same-sex marriage would benefit the local economy: "We don't want to balance our books by bringing the sex industry – whether it is same sex or not – to the Virgin Islands",<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stjohnsource.com/content/news/local-news/2014/07/24/one-voice-rallies-against-marriage-equality-bill|agency=St. John Source|title='One Voice' Rallies Against Marriage-Equality Bill|date=July 24, 2014|accessdate=November 3, 2014|first=James|last=Garner}}</ref>
